To generate new data points by varying target_material and target_thickness, scaling pulse_width and energy. Then, control spot_size, intensity, power, and cutoff_energy.
One possible solution is to use Gaussian process regression (GPR) or Bayesian Gaussian process regression (BGP). This method allows us to generate new data points by varying two features at a time. First, we randomly sample from the GP prior density function that is Gaussian with mean zero and covariance function that decays as 1/r^2. We can control the variance of this prior function using hyperparameters such as the inverse-Gaussian process precision (inverse-scale parameter) and a smoothing kernel length scale parameter, which we refer to as the length scale parameter. The GP is trained on existing data points, then we sample from this GP prior density function, and obtain new samples by varying target_material and target_thickness values randomly sampled according to the sampled data point, using the GP prior density function and the GP density as a reference function.
